    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</placeName>
                    <date>Dec 28 <hi rend="superscript">.</hi> 1877</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I thank you sincerely for your never-failing kindness in sending me your valuable works. I am sure that the one received to day will interest me greatly, judging from the extract given in the “Revue des Sciences”—<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>I remain, dear Sir | with the greatest respect | Yours faithfully | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Gaudry sent a copy of his book <hi rend="italic">Les enchaînements du monde animal dans les temps géologiques: mammifères tertiaires</hi> (Series in the animal world over geological time: tertiary mammals; <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9415.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">Gaudry 1878</ref>). CD’s copy is in the Darwin Library–Down. An extract from the book, ‘Les ruminants et leurs parents’ (Ruminants and their parents; <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_10465.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Gaudry 1877</ref>), appeared in <hi rend="italic">La Revue scientifique de la France et de l’étranger</hi>, 15 December 1877; CD’s annotated copy is in the Darwin Pamphlet Collection–CUL.</note>
        </div>  
      
